<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="151" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,310,400,426]" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,400,426]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[188,1399,447,615]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">
Among other species of 
<emphasis box="[477,585,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Raphirus</emphasis>
Stephens, 1829, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov, 2022" authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2022" box="[788,894,447,473]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viator" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[788,894,447,473]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Q. viator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[902,993,447,473]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Fauvel, 1875" authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coloratus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Quedius coloratus</emphasis>
Fauvel, 1875
</taxonomicName>
and all allied species, from which it can easily be distinguished by the structure of the aedeagus, namely by the wider apical portion of the median lobe with a sharper apex, rows of peg setae converging with each other in the middle portion (not parallel-sided), and the apex of the paramere almost reaching the apex of the median lobe (
<figureCitation box="[723,849,588,614]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[190,233,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[193,1383,550,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-69@11.[189,1398,543,1890]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 3. Quedius viator sp. nov., holotype (ZIN). A. Habitus. B–D. Aedeagus. B. From parameral side. C. Apical portion of paramere (underside). D. Lateral view. E. Sternite VIII. F. Tegite X. G. Sternite IX. Scale bars: A = 1 mm; B–G = 0.5 mm.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658773" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658773/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Fig. 3B–D</figureCitation>
) (for more details see section ‘Comparison’).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="151" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,324,653,679]" box="[189,324,653,679]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,653,679]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,653,679]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[188,1398,700,761]" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">
The name is the Latin noun ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2022" box="[522,592,700,725]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viator">
<emphasis box="[522,592,700,725]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">viator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ (= ‘traveller’) that refers to the fact that the newly described species, presumably closely related to a group of Mediterranean species, appears far away, in Middle Asia (
<figureCitation box="[1313,1383,735,761]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[188,232,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1238,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-248@10.[189,1398,1238,1924]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 2. Distribution map showing the type localities of Quedius gissaricus sp. nov. (red circle) and Q. viator sp. nov. (violet circle)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658771" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658771/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="151">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
